  <div class="article-content">
    <section id="introduction" class="reveal">
  <p>You will never build bone again. Not after roughly age twenty. Whatever skeletal architecture you carry into your third decade is the ceiling — the permanent upper limit of your structural capital. The body does not offer a second window. There is no remediation program, no supplement stack, no midlife intervention that restores what was not built during the years it could have been. Adolescents accumulate 40 to 60 percent of their adult bone mass during puberty alone, and 90 percent of peak bone mass is consolidated by age 18. After that, the construction crew leaves and does not come back.</p>
  <p>This is not a metaphor. It is physiology. And it is the reason a growing body of research — culminating in a landmark 2026 study published in the <em>Journal of the Endocrine Society</em> — demands attention that it has not yet received. The question that body of research is now forcing into focus: what happens when a class of synthetic chemicals, detectable in the blood of approximately 97 percent of Americans according to the CDC, is quietly interfering with bone construction during the only years that construction can occur?</p>
  <p>The chemicals in question are per- and polyfluoroalkyl substances — PFAS. There are over 12,000 individual compounds in the family. They have been used since the 1940s in nonstick coatings, food packaging, firefighting foam, water-resistant textiles, and dozens of industrial applications. They do not break down. They accumulate in tissue. And they have now been physically detected not just in blood, not just in breast milk, but inside human bone itself — a finding that transforms what might otherwise be an ambient contamination story into something considerably more specific and considerably more troubling.</p>
  <p>Girls, it turns out, are bearing a disproportionate share of whatever burden is being imposed. The reasons are not mysterious. They are mechanistically explicable. And the implications, if the science holds, are the kind that tend to arrive in public consciousness about thirty years after they should have.</p>
</section>

<section id="the-window" class="reveal">
  <h2>The Window, and What It Means to Miss It</h2>
  <p>Dr. Jessie P. Buckley, an epidemiologist at UNC Gillings School of Global Public Health and lead author of the 2026 study, puts it with the directness of someone who has spent years watching people not quite grasp the stakes: "After you're born, you start to accrue bone density, and you do it really rapidly through adolescence. Then after around age 20 or so, you have reached all the bone density you'll ever get, and it's all downhill after that."</p>
  <p>The clinical implications of that downhill trajectory are not abstract. A 10 percent increase in peak bone mass can postpone the onset of osteoporosis by 13 years. Run the arithmetic in reverse: a 6.4 percent reduction in bone density during childhood doubles the risk of fractures in adulthood. Osteoporosis currently affects over 200 million adults worldwide. The fractures it causes — hip, spine, wrist — are not merely painful. They are, particularly in the elderly, frequently fatal or permanently disabling. The foundation for all of it, good or bad, is laid before a person is old enough to vote.</p>
  <p>This is why the pediatric and adolescent bone-building window is not a footnote in developmental biology. It is the whole story. And it is why the question of what PFAS are doing to that window is not a niche environmental concern. It is a public health question of the first order.</p>
  <p>Buckley's 2026 study — the HOME Study, a prospective birth cohort of 218 children in Cincinnati — found that higher blood PFOA levels at birth, at age 3, at age 8, and at age 12 were all independently associated with lower forearm bone density at age 12. The effect was present regardless of when during childhood the exposure occurred. PFAS mixture exposure at ages 8 and 12 was linked to lower bone mineral density across all measured sites. The association was significantly stronger in females than in males. The beta coefficient for PFOA at age 8 was –0.54 (95% CI, –0.91 to –0.16) — a statistically robust signal in a field where small sample sizes routinely swamp the noise.</p>

  <aside class="pull-quote reveal"><p>"These chemicals may be causing folks to not reach their genetic potential for bone density, potentially raising risk for fractures and osteoporosis in older adulthood." — Dr. Jessie P. Buckley, UNC Gillings School of Global Public Health</p></aside>

  <p>The HOME Study is not alone. A 2023 longitudinal study from USC Keck School of Medicine, published in <em>Environmental Research</em>, followed 304 Hispanic adolescents with an average age of 11 and found that for each doubling of baseline PFOS concentration, participants showed an average decrease in bone mineral density of 0.003 g/cm² per year at follow-up. A 2025 cross-sectional analysis of 1,212 adolescents aged 12 to 19 drawn from NHANES 2011–2018 data, published in <em>Environmental Research</em>, found that co-exposure to six PFAS significantly reduced BMD across 11 bone sites, with sex-specific patterns and PFDeA identified as the dominant contributor to the combined effect specifically in girls. A Faroe Islands longitudinal birth cohort of 366 children, led by Annelise Blomberg of Harvard and Lund University and funded by NIEHS, found that higher PFAS concentrations at 18 months and 5 years were associated with decreased bone mass density at age 9, with the strongest effects for PFOA and PFNA.</p>
  <p>These are not the same study replicated. They are different populations, different geographies, different methodologies, different PFAS compounds — converging on the same signal.</p>
</section>

<section id="why-girls" class="reveal">
  <h2>Why Girls, and Why It Is Not a Coincidence</h2>
  <p>The sex disparity in these findings is consistent enough across independent studies that it demands explanation rather than notation. Girls are not simply more exposed. They are more vulnerable during the specific developmental window when exposure matters most, for reasons that are grounded in endocrinology.</p>
  <p>Girls reach peak bone accrual earlier than boys. Their skeletal development is more tightly and temporally coupled to estrogen signaling — the hormonal surge of puberty is the primary driver of the rapid bone mineralization that occurs between roughly ages 10 and 14. PFAS are endocrine-disrupting chemicals. They suppress estrogen, testosterone, and thyroid hormones, all of which are critical regulators of bone remodeling. Disrupt estrogen signaling during the pubertal bone accrual window in a girl, and you are not disrupting a background process. You are interfering with the primary mechanism of the primary event.</p>
  <p>The Project Viva cohort study — 484 children, 50 percent female, from a Boston-area population, published in <em>Environmental Science and Technology</em> in 2025 — found that females with higher PFOA and PFDA had lower early adolescent BMD Z-scores, and females with a higher overall PFAS burden score had both lower late adolescent BMD and slower bone accrual over time. The accrual rate matters as much as the snapshot. A girl who is building bone more slowly during the years she should be building it fastest is not just behind at age 12. She may arrive at age 20 with a permanently lower ceiling.</p>
  <p>Emily Beglarian, a PhD student at USC Keck School of Medicine and a researcher on the longitudinal cohort work, noted that "many existing studies haven't included participants this young, but we're now able to see that this association is already happening at a time when bones are supposed to be developing." The pre-pubertal and early pubertal window — roughly ages 8 to 12 — appears to carry the greatest bone-impairing impact, particularly in girls. This is not coincidental timing. It is the window.</p>
</section>

<section id="mechanisms" class="reveal">
  <h2>Four Mechanisms, One Skeleton</h2>
  <p>Epidemiological associations are suggestive. Mechanisms are explanatory. The science here has both, and the mechanistic picture is detailed enough to be taken seriously.</p>
  <p>The first pathway is the one already described: endocrine disruption. PFAS suppress sex hormones and thyroid hormones. In girls, suppressed estrogen during puberty directly impairs the hormonal signaling that drives osteoblast activity — the bone-building side of the remodeling equation.</p>
  <p>The second pathway involves peroxisome proliferator-activated receptor gamma, or PPARγ. PFAS activate PPARγ, which governs the fate of bone marrow mesenchymal stem cells. When PPARγ is activated, those stem cells preferentially differentiate into adipocytes — fat cells — rather than osteoblasts. The construction workforce is being redirected. Fewer osteoblasts means less bone formation, independent of any hormonal effect.</p>
  <p>The third pathway runs through PPARα. A 2025 study published in <em>Toxicology Reports</em> found that an environmentally relevant PFAS mixture promoted osteoclastic differentiation of bone marrow macrophages through PPARα activation. Osteoclasts are the cells that resorb bone — the demolition crew. GenX, one of the replacement PFAS compounds introduced after legacy chemicals were phased out, had the highest propensity to induce osteoclastogenesis in the study. In vivo, GenX and PFHxS exposure reduced trabecular and cortical bone thickness in mice and disrupted bone mineral composition. More osteoclasts, fewer osteoblasts: the remodeling balance tips toward net loss.</p>
  <p>The fourth pathway is perhaps the most specific and the most underappreciated. A 2020 study in <em>Scientific Reports</em> found that PFOA competes directly with calcitriol — active vitamin D — at the vitamin D receptor binding site, causing a 10 percent reduction in binding as measured by surface plasmon resonance. This is not a downstream effect. PFOA is physically displacing the molecule that vitamin D needs to bind in order to signal. The consequence: altered vitamin D-responsive gene expression in osteoblasts and reduced mineralization in human osteoblasts when PFOA is co-incubated with vitamin D. Vitamin D is not a wellness supplement. It is a fundamental regulator of calcium absorption and bone mineralization. Functionally impairing its receptor during the years of peak bone accrual is not a trivial insult.</p>

  <div class="info-card my-12 reveal">
    <h4 class="font-serif text-lg font-semibold mb-3 text-primary-700 dark:text-primary-400">Four Converging Mechanisms: How PFAS May Impair Bone Development</h4>
    <ul class="space-y-2 text-sm">
      <li><strong>Endocrine disruption:</strong> PFAS suppress estrogen, testosterone, and thyroid hormones — all critical regulators of bone remodeling. In girls, disrupted estrogen signaling during puberty directly impairs osteoblast-driven bone formation at its peak.</li>
      <li><strong>PPARγ activation:</strong> PFAS activate PPARγ, shifting bone marrow stem cells away from osteoblast (bone-building) differentiation toward adipocyte (fat cell) formation — reducing the supply of bone-forming cells.</li>
      <li><strong>PPARα-driven osteoclastogenesis:</strong> PFAS activate PPARα, promoting the formation of osteoclasts — bone-resorbing cells — tipping the remodeling balance toward net bone loss. GenX showed the highest osteoclastogenic potency in a 2025 <em>Toxicology Reports</em> study.</li>
      <li><strong>Vitamin D receptor competition:</strong> PFOA competes directly with calcitriol at the vitamin D receptor binding site, causing a 10% reduction in binding (surface plasmon resonance, 2020 <em>Scientific Reports</em>), impairing mineralization in human osteoblasts.</li>
      <li><strong>Direct skeletal accumulation:</strong> PFAS have been physically detected inside human bone tissue, suggesting the potential for direct, localized skeletal toxicity beyond systemic hormonal effects.</li>
    </ul>
  </div>

  <p>And then there is the accumulation finding. Dr. Lida Chatzi, Professor of Population and Public Health Sciences at USC and director of the USC Superfund Research Program for PFAS, has noted that "PFAS have been detected directly in human bone tissue, suggesting they may accumulate in bone and potentially contribute to skeletal toxicity." This is not a blood-level association story. The chemicals are in the skeleton. What they are doing there, at what concentrations, over what duration — these are questions the research is only beginning to ask.</p>
</section>

<section id="magnitude" class="reveal">
  <h2>The Magnitude Problem</h2>
  <p>One of the most clarifying — and most uncomfortable — findings in this literature is the comparative magnitude of the observed effects. Buckley has stated it plainly: "These BMD scores are as large or larger than those reported for other recognized influences on adolescent bone health, such as diet quality, physical activity or genetic risk."</p>
  <p>Read that again. The bone density deficits associated with PFAS exposure are comparable to, or larger than, the deficits associated with poor diet, low physical activity, or adverse genetic predisposition. Pediatricians counsel parents about calcium intake. School health programs promote weight-bearing exercise. Genetic risk for osteoporosis is screened and managed. PFAS exposure is not being managed. It is not being screened. It is not, in most clinical contexts, being discussed at all.</p>
  <p>The fracture implications are not speculative. Based on prior research, the BMD differences associated with high versus low PFAS exposure are similar in magnitude to roughly 10 to 30 percent higher odds of forearm fracture in childhood. A 2024 study in <em>Frontiers in Public Health</em>, analyzing 622 participants aged 12 to 19 from NHANES data, found that PFOA was negatively correlated with total bone density and concluded that improper PFAS exposure during childhood and adolescence could raise osteoporosis risk in adulthood. The 2019 Project Viva study in <em>Environmental Health Perspectives</em> — 576 children in a Boston-area cohort, one of the first to evaluate environmental exposures in relation to bone health in childhood — found higher PFAS plasma concentrations associated with lower BMD Z-scores, with a stronger association in females than males.</p>

  <aside class="pull-quote reveal"><p>"PFAS are ubiquitous — we are all exposed to them. We need to eliminate that exposure to allow our youth to reach their full potential in terms of bone development." — Dr. Lida Chatzi, USC</p></aside>

  <p>The cumulative picture, across multiple cohorts, multiple countries, multiple analytical approaches, is not a single anomalous finding. It is a pattern. Annelise Blomberg, whose Faroe Islands work was funded by NIEHS, concluded that "early PFAS exposures may impact the accrual of bone mass density throughout childhood, which can impact long-term risk of osteoporosis. The consistent associations found in this and previous studies support the possibility that bone may be a target tissue for developmental PFAS toxicity in humans."</p>
</section>

<section id="complications" class="reveal">
  <h2>What the Data Does Not Say Cleanly</h2>
  <p>The observational design is a real limitation. State it once: these studies cannot establish causation. Confounding variables — diet, physical activity, socioeconomic status, co-exposure to other environmental chemicals — may explain some portion of the observed associations. The flagship 2026 HOME Study had 218 participants, a sample size that limits statistical power and generalizability. A 2020 Bayesian weighted quantile sum regression study of 499 adults from NHANES 2013–2014 found no evidence of association between a PFAS mixture and bone mineral density in the overall population or in vulnerable subgroups, highlighting that the adult data is inconsistent in ways the pediatric data is not. Bone density measured at age 12 is before peak bone mass is reached; whether the observed deficits persist, widen, or close by late adolescence remains an open question.</p>
  <p>The paradoxical findings deserve more than a footnote. Some studies have found positive associations between certain PFAS — PFHxS and PFOS at age 3, for instance — and higher BMD at some bone sites. The HOME Study found that high PFAS at age 3, likely reflecting breast milk transfer, was associated with higher BMD at age 12. This is not a rounding error. It complicates the narrative in ways that are scientifically important: timing matters, source of exposure matters, and the specific compound matters. The relationship between PFAS and bone is not uniformly negative across all chemicals, all ages, and all sites. Some in vitro studies found no disturbance in osteogenic differentiation of osteoblasts after PFOA exposure, suggesting the mechanism may act primarily through osteoclast activation rather than osteoblast suppression — a distinction with potential treatment implications.</p>
  <p>Most of the existing research has focused on legacy PFAS — PFOA and PFOS — that have been largely phased out in the United States since the early 2000s. The bone health effects of the replacement compounds, including GenX and other short-chain PFAS, are largely unstudied in human populations. The 2025 <em>Toxicology Reports</em> study found GenX had the highest osteoclastogenic potency of the compounds tested. Whether that translates to human skeletal outcomes at environmental exposure levels is not yet known.</p>
  <p>These caveats are real. They are also insufficient to dismiss the signal. The consistency across independent cohorts, the mechanistic plausibility, the sex-specific patterns that align with known biology, and the magnitude of the observed effects relative to recognized risk factors together constitute a body of evidence that warrants considerably more urgency than it has received.</p>

  <div class="info-card my-12 reveal">
    <h4 class="font-serif text-lg font-semibold mb-3 text-primary-700 dark:text-primary-400">The Evidence at a Glance</h4>
    <ul class="space-y-2 text-sm">
      <li><strong>2026 HOME Study (Buckley, UNC / <em>Journal of the Endocrine Society</em>):</strong> N=218. Higher PFOA at birth, age 3, 8, and 12 all associated with lower forearm BMD at age 12. Effect stronger in females. Beta = –0.54 at age 8 (95% CI, –0.91 to –0.16).</li>
      <li><strong>2023 USC Keck longitudinal study (<em>Environmental Research</em>):</strong> N=304 Hispanic adolescents. Each doubling of baseline PFOS associated with –0.003 g/cm² per year BMD decrease.</li>
      <li><strong>2025 NHANES cross-sectional study (<em>Environmental Research</em>):</strong> N=1,212 adolescents aged 12–19. Six-PFAS co-exposure reduced BMD across 11 bone sites; PFDeA dominant contributor in girls.</li>
      <li><strong>2022 Faroe Islands cohort (Blomberg, Harvard/Lund / <em>Environmental Health</em>):</strong> N=366. Higher PFAS at 18 months and age 5 associated with lower BMD at age 9; strongest effects for PFOA and PFNA.</li>
      <li><strong>2025 Project Viva (<em>Environmental Science and Technology</em>):</strong> N=484, 50% female. Higher PFOA and PFDA associated with lower early adolescent BMD Z-scores in females; higher PFAS burden associated with slower bone accrual.</li>
      <li><strong>2019 Project Viva (<em>Environmental Health Perspectives</em>):</strong> N=576. Higher PFAS plasma concentrations associated with lower BMD Z-scores; stronger association in females.</li>
    </ul>
  </div>
</section>

<section id="policy-gap" class="reveal">
  <h2>The Gap Between What We Know and What We Are Doing</h2>
  <p>The U.S. Geological Survey has found PFAS in at least 45 percent of U.S. tap water. The CDC places the prevalence of detectable PFAS in Americans at approximately 97 percent. The EPA finalized maximum contaminant levels for six PFAS in drinking water in 2024 — the first federal drinking water standards for these compounds. Jesse Goodrich, an assistant professor at USC Keck School of Medicine, has noted that "even though there are some regulations that are lowering levels, we really need larger policies to fully eradicate these, if possible." The regulatory apparatus is moving. It is moving slowly, and it is moving primarily in response to cancer and immune endpoints that have a longer evidentiary history. The bone endpoint is newer, less established in the regulatory literature, and involves a harm that is diffuse, delayed, and impossible to attribute to any single exposure event.</p>
  <p>This is the structural problem. Osteoporosis at 65 does not come with a receipt. No one will be able to point to a specific water source, a specific product, a specific year of exposure and say: this is where the deficit was created. The harm is probabilistic and population-level, distributed across decades, and borne most heavily by women — who already face higher baseline osteoporosis risk — whose adolescent bone accrual was quietly impaired by chemicals they had no knowledge of and no ability to avoid.</p>
  <p>The mitigation data is real but modest. The 2025 Project Viva analysis found that greater dairy consumption and exercise may partially reduce the bone-impairing impacts of PFAS. This is not nothing. It is also not reassuring. The protective effect appears more robust in males than in females — which is, given everything else in this literature, almost a cruel irony. The population most vulnerable to the exposure is also the population least protected by the available behavioral countermeasures. And "eat more dairy and exercise" is not a policy response to a contaminant present in the blood of virtually every child in the country.</p>

  <aside class="pull-quote reveal"><p>"Adolescence is a key period for building strong bones, and achieving optimal bone mass during this time can reduce lifelong risks of fractures and osteoporosis." — Dr. Jessie P. Buckley</p></aside>

  <p>The timeline here is worth sitting with. PFAS have been recognized as endocrine-disrupting chemicals for decades. The critical importance of the adolescent bone-building window has been established in the medical literature for decades. The connection between endocrine disruption and impaired bone development is not a conceptual leap. And yet the first serious epidemiological studies examining PFAS specifically in relation to bone health in children began appearing only around 2019. The 2026 HOME Study — which Buckley describes as examining "periods of susceptibility" across the entire childhood exposure timeline — is among the most comprehensive to date. We are, in other words, approximately twenty years behind where we should be.</p>
  <p>Buckley's framing of the stakes is precise and, in its precision, devastating: "These chemicals may be causing folks to not reach their genetic potential for bone density." Genetic potential. The ceiling that biology set for each child, the maximum skeletal capital that their particular genome made possible — that potential is being foreclosed, quietly, before the child is old enough to understand what is being taken.</p>
  <p>You cannot go back and rebuild it. The window closes at twenty. And for a generation of children already carrying these chemicals in their blood and in their bones, the window is closing now.</p>
</section>

